eliminate summer soil moisture deficit in 1 ha plot with similar
adjacent control plot. We investigated the tree response to the
supplement irrigation with automatic branch chambers (16 chambers split
in treatment and control plots), sap flow sensors (SF; 40 trees) and
electronic dendrometers (20 trees) sensors.    Results from the first
treatment year showed a drought-typical decline in branch net
assimilation (An) and transpiration (T) in early summer (from ˜15
to ˜4 g C m-2h-1 and from 2 to 0.5 mm h-1, respectively in midday
values). However, upon the onset of the supplement irrigation in May, T
increased dramatically to ˜5 mm h-1, ˜2.5 times higher than
the peak wet season values. This increase was in correlation with the
